[center][size=99pt][b]hello,[/b][/size][/center] [b]Introduction[/b] Many people still have unorganized winterLove-based servers with them. So let's package them into different directories according (preferably) the category they should belong to.
[b]Packaging[/b] How do we do it? Let's look at an example below.
[code=Java]package packaging;
public class PackageExample {
public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println("I'm packaged."); }
}[/code]
Once you have created that class, save it under a folder named [tt]packaging[/tt] and nothing else or you will be returned with a [tt]NoClassDefFoundError[/tt] error if you try to run by using [tt]java PackageExample[/tt] instead of [tt]java packaging.PackageExample[/tt] (the one which you should use).
Additionally, you could have a package in another (also known as sub-packaging), as typed out below.
[code=java]package packaging.random;
public class RixxxRocks {
public static void derp() { System.out.println("I'm a derp."); }
}[/code]
[b]Using a package[/b] Now it's time to learn how to use a package! You followed the tutorial, right...? There are actually 2 ways to use a package but I shall teach you only one - importing. When you use the [tt]import[/tt] keyword, you can call classes only with the public modifier within the package. Let's try using the import method! Important: You cannot import sub-packages by just importing a package!
[code=java]package packaging;
import packaging.random.RixxxRocks; //import just the RixxxRocks class import packaging.random.*; //import all the public classes in the random library
public class PackageExample {
public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println("I'm packaged."); RixxxRocks.derp(); }
}[/code]
The output would read: [code]I'm packaged. I'm a derp.[/code]
[b]More[/b] Read up more on packaging [url=http://www.jarticles.com/package/package_eng.html]here[/url] or [url=http://download-llnw.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/package/index.html]here[/url]. Always remember to name classes with a capital letter for its first letter of each word! A package should always be in lower cases.
[b]Application (test)[/b] Now that you've learnt packaging, it's time to apply it on a server. Download this source: [url=http://www.mediafire.com/?iz4vmiiemw0]Cleaned WinterLove by jmood128[/url]. I'm choosing it because it's the cleanest one around.
Folder contents of the [tt]src[/tt] folder:
[ul][li]Client.java[/li] [li]Config.java[/li] [li]Cryption.java[/li] [li]GarbageCleaner.java[/li] [li]IOClient.java[/li] [li]IOHostList.java[/li] [li]IOThread.java[/li] [li]Item.java[/li] [li]LoadConfigFile.java[/li] [li]Misc.java[/li] [li]NPC.java[/li] [li]NPCHandler.java[/li] [li]NPCList.java[/li] [li]NpcThread.java[/li] [li]Player.java[/li] [li]PlayerHandler.java[/li] [li]Saver.java[/li] [li]Server.java[/li] [li]Stream.java[/li][/ul]
To test whether you have really learned anything, package that server (and of course import the used classes) into this: [img]http://i34.tinypic.com/2vtqn0z.jpg[/img]
Compile it with this new batch file (alternatively, you can use ANT but this batch file saves the hassle): [code=Build.bat]@echo off title Compiling... javac.exe -d bin/src src/com/server/Server.java src/com/server/io/*.java src/com/server/misc/*.java src/com/server/model/item/*.java src/com/server/model/npc/*.java src/com/server/model/player/*.java src/com/server/model/player/io/*.java src/com/server/model/player/save/*.java pause echo Done cls Build.bat[/code]
and run it with this: [code=Rune Server.bat]@echo off title Cleaned WinterLove cd bin/src java Server pause[/code]
If you can compile and run without any errors, congratulations, you have passed this test! Now you can proceed to package your own server - but remember, always make a backup before doing so! I cannot emphasize how important it is to make a backup.
